A chemical plant explosion in China's northeast led to lethal chemicals polluting the Songhua River, affecting 3.8 million residents in Harbin.
The responsible company, Jilin Petroleum, faces scrutiny.
Immediate actions include shutting down water supplies and allocating funds for cleanup.
China informed Russia of the pollution, emphasizing cooperation.
Measures to mitigate the pollution's impact include increased water discharge and monitoring.
Despite concerns, experts believe rural areas are less affected.
Efforts to combat environmental degradation are underway, with a focus on reducing pollutant emissions and ensuring safe drinking water.
The government is committed to long-term environmental protection.
